    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, the glove analogy helps. you mentioned the \"spooky action at a distance\" thing—can you explain a bit more about why that part was so controversial for scientists like Einstein? like why did it seem so weird or \"spooky\" to them compared to normal physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein found the idea \"spooky\" because it seemed to violate the universal speed limit of causality, which he believed was sacred. In his view, if you measure one particle and instantly know the state of its partner across the galaxy, information must be traveling faster than light, which he thought was impossible. He famously argued that quantum mechanics was an incomplete theory and that there must be \"hidden variables\" inside the particles that determined their states from the start, much like a pair of gloves where the left and right are already decided before you open the boxes.\n\nHowever, the controversy was settled by the work of John Bell, who devised a way to test whether nature was truly local or if those \"hidden variables\" existed. Experiments have consistently shown that the \"glove\" analogy fails; the particles don't have pre-determined states, and the connection is genuinely non-local. This means that the universe allows for a level of interconnectedness that defies our classical intuition, a fact that even Einstein couldn't accept until he was forced to admit that \"God does not play dice\" might be a bit too simple.\n\nDespite Einstein's objections, this \"spookiness\" is now a practical tool for quantum computing and cryptography,",
      "source": "target",
